revision.text:
In the law of [[tort]]s, '''bellwether trial''' is a [[Test case (law)|test case]] intended to try a widely contested issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://works.bepress.com/alexandra_lahav/3/|title=Bellwether Trials|author=Alexandra D. Lahav|accessdate=2012-10-10}}</ref> Bellwether [[Trial|trials]] are an increasingly common phenomenon in [[United States|U.S.]] [[Practice of law|legal practice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://product-liability.weil.com/mass-tort/the-spread-of-bellwether-trials/|title=The Spread of Bellwether Trials|author=Jeremy Grabill|date= May 18, 2011|accessdate=2012-10-10}}</ref>
Bellwether trials are especially common in [[Multidistrict Litigation]] (MDL) practice, where many cases have been consolidated for purposes of [[Discovery (law)|discovery]] and pretrial matters. In these MDL cases, it is not practical to prepare every case for trial. Several matters are, therefore, selected as bellwether cases and prepared for trial. They are then settled or tried and the results are used to shape the process for addressing the remaining cases.<ref>Manual for Complex Litigation, Fourth, §22.315</ref>
A bellwether trial is designed to achieve value ascertainment function for [[Settlement (litigation)|settlement]] purposes or to answer troubling [[Causation (law)|causation]] or liability issues common to a universe of [[Plaintiff|claimants]].<ref>In re Chevron U.S.A., Inc. F.3d 1016 (5th Cir. 1997).</ref> For the tried cases to achieve these purposes, it must be representative of all cases.
