{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Use Australian English|date=September 2012}} {{Infobox book| |name = Dot and the Kangaroo |title_orig = |translator = |image = Kangaroo ill-01.jpg | image_size = 200px |caption = Book illustration |author = [[Ethel Pedley]] |illustrator = Frank P. Mahony |cover_artist = |country = Australia |language = English |genre = [[Children's literature|Children's novel]] |publisher = [[Angus and Robertson]] |release_date = 1899 |english_release_date = |media_type = Print (Hardback and Paperback) |pages = 81 pp |isbn = 1-4191-1659-2 |oclc = 224601955 }}
'''''Dot and the Kangaroo''''' is a children's book written by [[Ethel Pedley|Ethel C. Pedley]] about a little girl named Dot who gets lost in the Australian [[outback]] and is eventually befriended by a [[kangaroo]] and several other [[marsupial]]s. The book was adapted into a stage production in 1924, and a film in 1977.<ref name="ReferenceA">Giannalberto Bendazzi, Cartoons: One Hundred Years of Cinema Animation, Indiana university Press, {{ISBN|0-253-20937-4}}</ref>
==Plot introduction== A 5-year-old girl named Dot is lost in the outback after chasing a hare into the wood and losing sight of her home. She is approached by a red kangaroo who gives her some berries to eat. Upon eating the berries, Dot is able to understand the language of all animals, and she tells the kangaroo her plight. The kangaroo, who has lost her own joey, decides to help little Dot despite her own fear of humans. The book is filled with criticism on negative human interference in the wild in 1884. [[Image:Dot and the Kangaroo, Author Page.jpg|center|thumb|A scan of a first edition copy of ''Dot and the Kangaroo'', which included a photograph of Pedley and a copy of her signature.]]
==Film adaptations== {{main article|Dot and the Kangaroo (film)}}
A film adaptation was released in 1977 directed by [[Yoram Gross]]. It combines animation with live action.
