{{Infobox ancient site | name = Cuauhtinchan | alternate_name = | image = | image_size = 300px | alt = | caption = | map = | map_type = Mesoamerica | map_alt = | map_caption = Location within [[Mesoamerica]] | map_size = | relief = | coordinates = {{coord|18|56|50.96|N|99|29|26.89|W|display=inline}} | map_dot_label = | location = [[Malinalco]], [[Mexico (state)|Mexico]],&nbsp;{{flag|Mexico}} | region = [[Mexico State]] | built = | abandoned = | epochs = Late Preclassic to Late Classic | cultures = | event = | excavations = | archaeologists = | architectural_styles = | architectural_details = | notes = | designation1 = | designation1_offname = | designation1_type = | designation1_criteria = | designation1_date = | delisted1_date = | designation1_partof = | designation1_number = | designation1_free1name = | designation1_free1value = | designation1_free2name = | designation1_free2value = | designation1_free3name = | designation1_free3value = | designation2 = | designation2_offname = | designation2_type = | designation2_criteria = | designation2_date = | delisted2_date = | designation2_partof = | designation2_number = | designation2_free1name = | designation2_free1value = | designation2_free2name = | designation2_free2value = | designation2_free3name = | designation2_free3value = | precolumbian = yes <!-- non-functional tracking parameter, do not remove/change --> }}
'''Cuauhtinchan Archeological Zone''' or '''Malinalco Archeological Zone''', located just west of the town center on a hill called '''Cerro de los Idolos''', which rises 215 meters above the town.<ref name="A-G-59">{{harvnb|Aguilar-Moreno|2009|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=SS_aCCujQ3gC&pg=PA59 59]}}</ref> On its sides are a number of pre-Hispanic structures built on terraces built into the hill. The main structures are at the top.<ref name="cdtravel">{{Cite web |url= http://www.cdtravel.net/turismo/arque/mal.htm |title= Zona Arqueológica de Malinalco Estado de México |publisher=CD Travel |language=Spanish |trans-title=Archeological Zone of Malinalco, State of Mexico |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225214156/http://www.cdtravel.net/turismo/arque/mal.htm|archivedate=25 December 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref> This is one of the most important Aztec sites and was discovered in 1933,<ref name="encanto">{{cite journal |year=2008 |title=Malinalco |journal= Mexico Desconocido Guia Especial Pueblos con Encanto Estado de Mexico |pages=3e8–43 |publisher= Grupo Editorial Impresiones Aéreas |location=Mexico City |issn=1870-9419 |language=Spanish }}</ref> and explored by José Garía Payón in 1935.<ref name="novo">{{cite book |title= The State of Mexico |last=Novo |first=Gerardo |author2=Jorge de la Luz |year=2002 |publisher= Ediciones Nueva Guia SA de CV |location=Mexico City |isbn=968-5437-26-2 |pages=49–53 }}</ref> The visible complex dates from the [[Aztec Empire]] but the site’s use as a ceremonial center appears to be much older.<ref name="novo"/> The sanctuary complex was built from the mid 15th century to the beginnings of the 16th. To get to the Cerro de los Idolos one must climb 426 stairs up 125 meters.<ref name="guiaedomex">{{cite journal |year=2007 |title=Malinalco |journal= Mexico Desconocido Guia Estado de Mexico |volume=136 |pages=22–31 |publisher= Grupo Editorial Impresiones Aéreas |location=Mexico City |issn=1870-9400 |language=Spanish }}</ref> Along the stairway leading to the site, there are signs with area’s history written in Spanish, English and Nahuatl. The site contains six buildings.<ref name="Aguilar-Moreno">{{Cite book |author=Aguilar-Moreno, Manuel|year=2009|chapter=Chapter 5: Malinalco: A Place between Heaven and Earth|editor=Christie, Jessica Joyce|title=Landscapes of Origin in the Americas: Creation Narratives Linking Ancient Places and Present Communities|publisher=University of Alabama Press|location=Tuscaloosa, Alabama|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=SS_aCCujQ3gC&pg=PA57 57&ndash;76]|isbn=978-0-8173-1673-0}}</ref> The Cuauhcalli or House of the Eagles, which dates from 1501,<ref name="A-G-64">{{harvnb|Aguilar-Moreno|2009|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=SS_aCCujQ3gC&pg=PA64 64]}}</ref> is the main building, which is significant in that it is carved out of the hill itself.<ref name="encanto"/> The building is in the shape of a truncated pyramid,<ref name="noguez">{{cite journal |last=Noguez |first=Xavier |year=2006 |title=El templo monolítico de Malinalco, Estado de México |trans-title=The monolithic temple of Malinalco, Mexico State |journal=Arqueología Mexicana |volume=78 |pages=68–73 |url=http://www.arqueomex.com/S2N3nMalinalco78.html |language=Spanish |accessdate=2009-10-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103100544/http://arqueomex.com/S2N3nMalinalco78.html |archivedate=2010-01-03 |df= }}</ref> built this way due to the lack of space on the hill.<ref name="cdtravel"/> The monolithic Cuauhcalli has been compared to the [[Ellora Caves|Ellora]] in [[India]], [[Petra]] on the shores of the [[Dead Sea]] and [[Abu Simbel]] in [[Egypt]].<ref name="novo"/> This was a sanctuary for the Eagle Warriors for rites such as initiation.<ref name="encanto"/> A thirteen-step staircase leading into this temple is flanked by side struts.<ref name="novo"/> and two feline sculptures that face the plaza in front.<ref name="noguez"/> The Cuauhcalli consists of two rooms, one rectangular and the other circular, with an opening in the wall between the two. After being carved out of the rock, the walls and ceiling were covered in stucco and painted with murals, most of which are almost completely gone.<ref name="cdtravel"/> In the upper part, the entrance is symbolized by the open jaws of a serpent, complete with fangs, eyes and a forked tongue, which was painted red.<ref name="novo"/> This upper portion is covered by a thatched roof of the grass the area is named for.<ref name="noguez"/>
== Architecture == Just inside of the entrance, on the east side, there is a sculpture of a serpent’s head on which rests the remains of a statue of an Eagle Warrior. To the west, there is another sculpture in the shape of a large pedestal, symbolizing a tlapanhuéhuetl (war drum). Above this is a sculpture of a [[cipactli]], which is a primeval being, occasionally called a “monster of the earth.” The cipactli is holding up a person, of which only the sandals remain.<ref name="noguez"/> It is thought the two statues functioned as standards. Further inside is a bench that surrounds a space similar to a [[hemicycle]].<ref name="A-G-64" /> The horseshoe bench has four sculptures, the most outstanding one being an eagle that faces the entrance. Two others are also of eagles while the fourth is a jaguar.<ref name="noguez"/> The jaguar statue has its skin spread out as if it were a mounted trophy.<ref name="novo"/> Behind the eagles there is a [[cuauhxicalli]] or sacred vessel in which to put the hearts of sacrifice victims, who then turn into messengers of the sun. The orientation of the building relates to the movement of the stars. Before it was covered with a thatched roof to preserve it, openings in the walls provoked light phenomena at certain times such as at the summer solstice.<ref name="encanto"/>
From here was found a large wooden [[huéhuetl]] or ceremonial war drum, which is now in the Museum of Anthropology and History in the [[Mexiquense Cultural Center]] in Toluca.<ref name="cdtravel"/> At the spring and fall equinoxes some 5,000 to 7,000 people visit the site.<ref name="solis">{{Cite news |title= Ambulantaje, basura y daños en las zonas arqueológicas |first=Juan |last=Solis |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/cultura/w47951.html |newspaper=El Universal |location=Mexico City |date=2006-03-06 |accessdate=2009-10-29 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Wandering vendors, trash and damage at archeological zones }}</ref> The conical thatched roof that covers the main building is a reproduction of the kind of roof it probably had in antiquity, but the shed-like porch is less faithful to the original.<ref name="townsend">{{cite book |last1=Townsend |first1=Richard F. |editor1-first=Elizabeth H. |editor1-last=Boone |title= The Art and Iconography of Late Post-Classic Central Mexico |year=1982 |publisher= Dumbarton Oaks |location= Washington, DC |pages=119–120 |chapter= Malinalco and the Lords of Tenochtitlan }}</ref> Despite acts of vandalism, the interior of this building is still in good condition.<ref name="noguez"/>
