[[File:Roman Empire - Africa Proconsularis (125 AD).svg|thumb|right|Africa Proconsularis (125 AD)]]'''Vartana''' (''Vertare[n]sis'') was a [[Roman Empire|Roman]]-[[Berbers|Berber]] [[civitas|town]] in [[Byzacena]], [[Africa (Roman province)|Africa Proconsulare]]. It is identified with stone ruins in the area of Srâa-Ouartane, [[Tunisia]].

==Bishopric==
The city of Vartana (also known as Vertara<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/former/t1956.  Titular Episcopal See of  Vertara ] at GCatholic.org.</ref>) was also the seat of an ancient [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[diocese]]. Only one [[bishop]] is known to us from [[Ancient history|antiquity]]. Since 1933 the diocese has been reestablished in name at least and a bishop has been appointed there ever since.<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/former/t1938.htm   Titular Episcopal See of Vartana] at GCatholic.org.</ref>

Bishop Vetalis is recorded as attendee to a Church Council in 314.<ref>Henri Irénée Marrou, André Mandouze, Anne-Marie La Bonnardière Prosopographie de l'Afrique chrétienne (303-533) (Éditions du Centre national de la recherche scientifique, 1 Jan. 1982) p1220.</ref>

Bishop [[Leo Hale Taylor]] became the first of the new bishops on February 26, 1934. The current bishop is [[Giovanni Moretti (bishop)|Giovanni Moretti]] (9 Sep 1971 Appointed - ), who succeeded bishop [[Carlo Minchiatt]] (1969 - 1971).

